This paper deals with ranking algorithms and network structure analysis of Wikipedia articles, which are related to persons and their activity fields. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). The paper also involves information retrieval (IR) techniques for ranking, which suggests cs.IR (Information Retrieval) as the second likely sub-category. The paper also mentions natural language processing (NLP) and computational linguistics (CL) for analyzing multilingual editions of Wikipedia, which suggests cs.CL (Computation and Language) as the third likely sub-category. The paper also involves data-driven approaches and analysis of large datasets, which suggests cs.DL (Digital Libraries) as the fourth likely sub-category. Finally, the paper also involves analysis of cultural interconnections and diversity, which suggests cs.SD (Sound and Music Computing) as the fifth likely sub-category.
